A Republican Strategy to Obstacle Obama's Reelection
The Republican leaders justified their policy on the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers this to be a myth and states that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people dying from the fall of lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that regard, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what is happening in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing the federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of American governments enacted new laws that made the registration process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread since the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 2011 in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to submit an identity document with a photograph, as well as proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to vote on the day of scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to submit an identity document with photographs.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana law.
That is why the republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit an identity document with photography.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity card with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity card costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters aged between 18 and 29 do not have an identity card with photography.
And there's still more.
In many states the students, the voters who vote most for the Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to submit such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic voting.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, the Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service of assistance to voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, electoral registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in the drop in the registration rate for new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13 per cent of the electorate in the state.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same thing happened.
They represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, white people, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, account for only 46 per cent of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have ardently opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Ministry of Public Prosecution intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, it was possible to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the submission of an identity document with photograph.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the 2012 results in the key states.
A report from the Brennan Centre in 2011 shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required at the polling station to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty that these legislative amendments to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this respect, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
