Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "less evil" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We certainly know that there is a new particle and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still missing to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume that this is Higgs, because the chances of making mistakes seem to be few. We will see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and do not try too hard, because it will end in harm.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" which consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify the particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called farmers, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it could be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs that we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearer" bosons.
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" to make this boson appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide down the surface.
That's why we need an immense particle accelerator like CERN's (the great Hadron Collider is a 27km ring of circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to the door of a refrigerator by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like photon, by the way), do not.
However, what can all these investigations "provide"?, asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to look at the differences between MS observations and predictions.
Many, on the other hand, fervently want them to be found, as the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" covering certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation concerning gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of such investigations on our day-to-day lives is difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that it will have none.
For them to see: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution that their work would provoke.
They interviewed the scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle said, who worked in Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light catcher in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this capturer now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that we never know...
