But in all exchange a central authority controls and treats the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depository of accounting books, verifiers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction into that book.
This is due to the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file slices, i.e. a transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numeric footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "scramble" the set.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in deposit.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weighted actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, like the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Insitt in Israel analyzed the book and showed that about 80% bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant rebates" were launched.
"They changed $30,000," Jon Holmquist rejoices, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that coin, believes quite a lot in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to run in businesses, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to provide you with an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to review hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicted.
On the other hand, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, if this currency is successful.
