A Forceful Constitution in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And almost two years ago, Egypt has used a provisional text, several times modified, which undermines institutional stability and leads to judicial hurdles.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "treason his word" and "swimming the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a step towards speeding up the institutional and political crisis and accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time forcing the Brothers to renounce their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of recovering a popular and democratic legitimation while the controversy wreaks havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this remedy has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or I vote for my text or I hold full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in large majority, voted the text yesterday.
Most Liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not enforce their views.
Human rights representatives, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As was to be expected, the articles voted on were unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies in the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent clock was wrong.
The text, which was late yesterday, was still being voted on, contains 234 articles.
Article 2, which is the subject of all looks, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals are talking about hypocrisy and believe that it is only advertising.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers an advisory role on the Al-Azhar University, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not olemmas but academics, some of them formed in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We specifically refer to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to rule over all of this."
Beyond its religious nature, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that there are few compared to those who were during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers vested in the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Neither will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by associations for the defence of human rights.
These also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Furthermore, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing had been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to go out last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
The supporters of the head of state marched on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the world's navel and a sea of brine
The promised earth combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why Israel should be visited.
Reverence on the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pillar" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of the miracles of Jesus: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the appeasement of the storm and the crowded nets.
In this very place, Jesus appeared before his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers travel here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins in the Fortress of Antonio, the Pretorio, where the trial was conducted, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of crucifixion, to the Stone of the Anointing and to the place of burial of Jesus.
In this same place there is also the symbolic Christian Omblicus of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As it is tradition, people of different religions leave here notes with their desires, which will then come true.
Perform a vertical trip
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret shelter against enemies, which Herod the Great commanded to build in the year 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located in the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And get there by your own means, only those who are engaged in climbing can.
The others can reach this historic summit at the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a great influx of tourists.
Up to there, bus services are offered from the hill foot.
The overall length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly inhabited pagan gods.
Visiting unique museums
In this country there are about 300 museums.
On one trip you won't be able to visit all of them.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient manuscripts of the Dead Sea or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition of paintings he has canvases of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bathroom Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and swimmers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth passing through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops there.
The entrance is free, and no donations are categorically accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And they sound the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries where they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop from 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe throughout the year.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: at 417 m below the sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustains even those who can't swim.
The landscapes of the surroundings are truly beautiful.
People come here to spend treatment courses with salt water, brine and curative clays and strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to sort out their broken nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
The ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, is preserved on the Mediterranean coast.
For her was the famous sea route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he took a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your symbol "meism", fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find couples of newlyweds coming from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Cesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, do not worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to bring it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently $1-3,8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Low City with the High City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Travelling in any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night until sundown on Saturday, markets and shops close and public transportation disrupts your job.
But Sunday morning starts a new workweek.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, Falafel, which are balls of ground chickpea, fruits and vegetables.
Streets in Israeli cities do not see street dogs.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats who "walk to their liking" in an impressive way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Roosters love the crowded places and do not reject the golosinas.
The rental of a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, which goes out for $15 a day.
And the rent of a bike will come out for 15 shekels the day.
The entrances to the museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012 more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to travel the country and rested were U.S. citizens, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, amounting to over 51 per cent at the same rate as in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on 9 February 2011.
