While human rights MPs and defenders are discussing the consequences of the mandatory review law, there have already been perpetrators who trade with "false" certificates in the country.
Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law has come into force, according to which each immigrant worker must carry out a test to verify his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised in the Federal Immigration Service, examinations will be made compulsory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to carry out the examination of the language, if not the examination of Russian history and the basis of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
Citizens of countries where Russian is the official language are no exception.
This law shall not apply to persons who obtained their certificates of education and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
Utility, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Russian Pushkin Institute of Language, the University of the Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to come to the test in all cities, and right now more than 160 such centres are open in Russia.
The initiative on the introduction of the review was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, have often been able to ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring about?
What changes will make the knowledge of the language compulsory for both Russians and immigrants themselves?
First, representatives of the Immigration Service respond, which will reduce the number of people suffering from "work slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labour migrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defence of their rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will help resolve the problem of immigrant workers in 90 per cent of cases.
The problems are the immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the immigrant future will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, on the pretext of helping, put a "paid traveler" into a creepy, narrow cave, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working from 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they promise one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," confirms the head of the Immigration Directorate of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, Chief!
However, in the meantime many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they do not only know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also in their own language they write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much his fault but his own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to talk about dressing them, shoeing them and buying them what they need for school.
Upon reaching adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It's difficult, if you don't know the language, you recognize them.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as language law is concerned, rights defenders point to an important point.
Examinations will only be carried out for immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have such status, there will be no review and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden the passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false enrollment can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred roubles.
Russian police officers know that we usually carry false documents, are not registered and extortion cases appear.
