Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As far as local legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it cannot be precisely specified in what is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kind of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't mean any benefit to them to collaborate with our office, would it?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act mean for your Office? Is there any indication of its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there must be some delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new "non-economic risk detection" tool, whereby we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial or, rather, an embroil for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations "harden up" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional council operational programmes), and each law not respected in the field of public procurement meant violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal judgment, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this road leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently declared that the ODS would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, even the prime minister of the government cannot prevent the performance of the Office which has an obligation to carry out such checks and to demand obligations.
He can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but he can't say we'll do anything.
In the Public Procurement Act, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and that is what it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer because he does not meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. That is, in my opinion, what we lack.
