Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission in subsequent years.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, where, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name to one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dresin was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who the author of the proposal was, nor is the project known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for dresin start-up or braking.
Information about this drain is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
Based on the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation came to the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komite Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft military missile techniques and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemmy, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to Astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would devote itself to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) has sought to become a member of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year, the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He served this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach the 5 kg weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in summer 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rocket tests were initiated in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was going to be the object of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available to the scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available volume space was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B it was 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C it was 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first air tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonata after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week, the constitutional court suspended the law on social work.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
This therefore means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is found in the principle of free trade and free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of major differences in labour cost (wage) is economic strain.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and thus "causes a downturn" of the competitor's price in order to make it with most of the market and thereby increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, to move production abroad, buy there cheaper or disappear. The result is a high unemployment in those countries where the price of work, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, thus, it is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state is necessarily growing.
All of this gives rise to the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their desire to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create situations, in certain economies, in which the Governments of those countries are forced to compete in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population and thereby attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account social decline.
This is reflected above all in changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the private capital dictatorship, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees with regard to labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is already up to a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind was published in connection with the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The savings measures of virtually all the southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressed by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to malvive with a pessimal wage on the edge of society, in the hope that some day it will reach the private investor capital country.
Do you have to wonder where it's coming from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty goes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African countries continue to work for a tiny part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media allege that the state should not bring capital to the economy, which leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by entering control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence its selfishness in the political march and therefore throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in very powerful and omnipresent practice, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favor, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills to private legal enterprises, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation like the one that describes Appianos in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in times of Caesar and Pompei: "The state had been disintegrating and the administrations dealt with the force".
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread without hindrance and the people went to the polls with the beat-up vote beforehand ... "there were no people in a position to aspire to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls" ... "It began to speak seriously that the only remedy for such a serious situation was the autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man" ... Although Appianos thought of Pompei, Caesar went up to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, in the same way as in ancient times, is that the present society is based on disregarded preferences for the individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
Private capital is not in its essence capable of understanding and claiming the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes should therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th century.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The really demolishing fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the Public Procurement Act is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at international level and within the EU, the Czech Republic's government will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
