In November 1979 a group of Islamist students held the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
His release was going to be in exchange for the disastrous Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah away could not be allowed, since, if it did, it threatened the trust of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified even more with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
Incarcerated diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the US, its fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
Iran's failure contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by the director and actor Ben Affleck discusses an episode of this story, which has reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before the embassy was occupied, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated periple, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, to help a covert story with an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew who examined the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combination
The plan brought by the expert on "exfiltration" Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
For the lie to seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictitious production society had even a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other hand, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that came out well, a deception (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film the moods are combined. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits are shown emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were shaped the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, Hollywood typical scenes a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men brought to look at the situation at the negotiating table, in the office corridors, by phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respected director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Adiós petite, Adiós" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film where the action doesn't take place in Boston City, where it was created.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed directors of old movies above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "walks" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, transmits the emotion of the disconcert and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the tax team at the bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that a story explained does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And it's pretty well managed. Sometimes it adds something to reality: here everything doesn't go so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis occurs at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search after its track becomes a madness).
The weakness of Argo is the uncontrollability that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman play a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserve more space and are not, let alone, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, to value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, that's going to be hard.
As an evocation of a real history and as proof of how exaggerated notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is sufficient.
