Even the most everyday civil architects and engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it is like a day, in a French farm, we are faced with the proper by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric of few millimetres of thickness has been used in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands as a basis for holding the roots of the crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This thin fabric lasts two seasons and then it is discarded.
For the library this fabric was taken, for the first time in such quantities, until it obtained plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells of a new and sporty shoe and car mix.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
