This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give him that much importance because it's not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting in important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think that there has been such a drastic break-up as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to gain some respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country to which they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the other hand, the US has clearly been in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European nations?
