However, neither the Egyptians nor the whole world know very well what this 61-year-old engineer with a Ph.D. degree awarded by the University of Southern California really wants to save.
You mean to deprive the judiciary of your power?
In fact, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly made up of 100 predominantly Islamist members at a 15-hour night meeting, are truly worrying.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
But what does that mean, "principles"?
This was and continues to be open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the margin of legal manoeuvre that it carries, to impose a more strict interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what suggests a new article added: in all questions relating to sharia it is mandatory to consult the Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power throughout Sunni Islam.
It does not have to be so, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that - in fact - would result in the incapacity of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's dictatorship these courts served to exert a harsh repression of the opposition.
After the dictator's fall, up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As the draft establishes, the State must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values."
This is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the content of cinematography and literature.
Clearly, this is nothing but censorship.
Of course, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
Yet another forbids offending or slandering Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is unclear what an offence is and how it should be punished.
Equally questionable is the formulation that prohibits "offends to people"
Is it enough for a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Morsi for signature and that according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians to be submitted to referendum.
"The revolution is back"
The opposition has been closing ranks in the face of the superiority of Islamists for weeks now.
Ten thousand people gathered in an unusual harmony on Friday afternoon at Tahrir Square in Cairo and swore to fail the Act before it could come into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will end by winning," says Hamdin Sabbahi, who takes third place on the lists in the presidential elections.
The Nobel Peace Prize and former director of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, declared that the draft constitution should be "in the bucket of the trash of history".
Through Twitter he accused Morsi's followers of wanting to lead a "state coup against democracy."
"When he summons the referendum we will go to his palace and overthrow it," says oppositioner Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned," Egyptians quoted the opposition politician Chaled Ali in the media.
And a number of judges announced that they did not want to oversee the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Qur'an is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-protest; in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, at the University of Cairo.
Many women covered with a veil and supporters of the Salafists took part in it in the cry of: "the people demand the application of the divine law."
They demanded that Morsi "clean the country," while proclaiming, "the Qur'an is our constitution."
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where it began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is clear that Morsi's supporters did not want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim brothers claimed that both those who oppose the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their views loud and clear.
Now would have been the time to let the people decide in the ballot box which direction the country should follow.
In this sense, it seems that the draft Islamists have guaranteed the majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should actually have lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended Muslim brothers when they were held in prison or had to face a trial during Mubarak's dictatorship.
Not because he would share his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression `Human Rights' doesn't even appear in the new constitution," laments in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three powers of the State caused this lawyer to resign.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead to a new dictatorship in Egypt.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the President has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against him.
A protestant in Tahrir Square warns: "you are conceiving a monster that you cannot control."
The Norwegian rakfisk: the world's worst fish?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country has any connection with its greed for a highly malicious fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a mountain of dirty and wet football clothes.
Leave him there for a week.
Then you can smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway’s exquisites.
I find myself in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It is snowy. The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfisk is a salad trout that lets you ferment in water during, depending on how bad you prefer it, up to a year.
As it darkens and gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this food, so to speak, captivating.
"You eat raw and then drink an aquavit glass of a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city fireman who is also known as the "Rakfisk General", who organizes the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking from a large drink quantities.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," Havard says.
Drink can kill the smell.
I try some slices.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, it is not bad; it is not very different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
The rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, in which poverty hit Norway and in which, before refrigeration existed, the fish was stored during the autumn immersed in water and salt in hermetic barrels.
Later, in mid-winter, when it is already well fermented, it is removed and, obviously with the inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just one generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and mostly emigrated to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13 per cent are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of inhabitants of Sweden, the old rival and so far not much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be an important part of Norway's past, but rather a bad part.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, it's all expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you 10€ ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it to be.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name Anders Breivik, the extreme right-wing racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the event of July 22."
It is very difficult for the Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of theirs was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
After much of Norway's current wealth, there has been the growth since the early 1970s of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason why we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she passes rakfisk trays and, with her long blonde melena and her surprising blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like most people in this country, is flawless.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything except a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for future generations.
While everyone was was was was wasting money that they did not have during the years preceding the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
"While we can ski in winter and hiking in summer, we are happy," Anna says.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a carcased detour.
I'm in the snow doing tail to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, he comes back with that bad fish.
The hotel I'm staying in is one of the many places where rakfisk dinner is held, where the comensals vote for the best fish, or maybe the one that most test the nasal pits.
A TV has connected live with a presenter who carries a birdie and is surrounded by dishes of rakfisk.
It looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There are laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps defeated by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapors of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
While the incoming President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, is preparing to take office, the BBC correspondent, Will Grant, analyses the challenges facing the new president and the different expectations of his population.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad today.
In a city that, in the best circumstances, is already congested, since Monday a steel fence has been installed that cuts off several of the main roads that lead to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The objective, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their jobs, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has achieved good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is immersed in a war against drug trafficking that has already been charged some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," explained Peña Nieto earlier this week to the President of the United States, Barack Obama, in the Oval Office.
"I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal."
Before co-opting with the US President, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state, that of Mexico.
A very populated state with rapid growth, which surrounds the capital; Opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is remembered with affection.
Its residents attribute to it the merit of the growth of tourism in the place and of the construction of infrastructures.
To get to the city you can drive along one of the new roads of Mr. Peña Nieto, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and filled roads that have been rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with their name in the entrance of a modern polydeportive and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he can make a real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, deputy of the party of Mr. Peña Nieto, the PRI.
"In particular, in terms of security and economics, we expect the interesting and true change our country needs so much."
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was disbanded by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Mr Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, within the party there are many expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the ruling that the opposition lacks the essence of the new President.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He's a fantastic stateman and, above all, he's a person who knows how to listen."
However, on the other side of the state that is not the impression that many people have about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Neza City, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under elevated highway sections is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Early this year, military intervention was called for to assist in the fight against drug gangs operating in neighborhoods and violence against women.
In a desert plot, located next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in only the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was the governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for his violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
The critics of Mr. Peña Nieto say, at best, that he did not know how to deal with the problem of feminicide while in office.
The most critical are accusing their administration of making a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the deteriorated neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain tears as she shows me pictures of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I came to his house, it seemed as if his body had been cleaned," recalls Mrs. Buendia.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared."
As his mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana looks from the walls, next to a cross in which one reads a single word: Justice.
However, that is exactly what the family says it has been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me like I'm an old gossip, a whistleblower, a scoffer.
What they want is for one to simply accept what they say and to shut up."
"But that can't be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much neglect," he says.
The presidential band President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico for the past six years and the new President has promised to give them priority during his term of office.
"I hope he's the same type of president as he was when he was a governor," says PRI Olvera's deputy in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is exactly what the families of the victims of the Neza City fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, according to prosecutors
Prosecutors try to deal with reports of abuse of Bradley Manning during their prison stay
The trial focuses on the Manning period in Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leaking of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution conducted to Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of weekly visits by unit officers that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request to dismiss the case, given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already resulted in sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while he was in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is charged with stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In the Friday view, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at the military prison in Quantico, where he was incarcerated under maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the colostors as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, although officials asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the visiting officers had spoken to him about those problems and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I didn't mention any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Denise Lind Army, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council to examine the suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was in.
The military said that they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below the possible suicide surveillance, to ensure his protection and safety of others.
"I wanted the senior state to know that I was well and (wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... in order to be able to enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that he once lost consciousness because of heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world only fell to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning stated that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said that he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a pair of panties, some clothes and their glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since he was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from the outside pointing to his eyes as he slept.
He said that if the lodgers couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer submitted in January 2011 a formal complaint about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in the Thursday statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced for a morning count to stand naked in front of the lodgers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the order given to him by the janitor that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his scarves to self-injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, his scarves, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers are hoping that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he has experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted on the war council, which is expected to begin in the beginning of next year.
The defence stated that it intended to have Manning plead guilty to minor offences and to defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was retained in accordance with the rules of application for any detainee under maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully causing the publication of information on the Internet, filtering information from the national defense and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
Affirms that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; they say they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
In a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely come down from the esplanade and arrived at the immigration processing area and was already completely confused.
Some posters pointed the way to two tails: one for "Mexicans" and another for "Foreigners".
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where I was supposed to go.
Having grown up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" all my life.
These are ethnic shorthands, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my New York friends call themselves "Italian."
Later I decided to "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, the shorthand or the scripts were not necessary.
He was simply an American.
I speak Spanish. Good enough to handle me during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought at that time this week that Mexico’s elected President Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as always the leaders of these two countries gather, it was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also desiring to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at the moment it is so likely that a Mexican stays in Mexico as if he ventured to go to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style commercial bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to yield half of its territory to the point of a gun.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not in minutes, the elements they remember are everywhere.
So at the moment when a U.S. official says anything that leads to the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the children of Moctezuma stand at war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is that they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking grudge?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason that there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere in our family tree, there was one person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was locked at the door of opportunities in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor people, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
Furthermore, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the ruling class elite do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulder as if we were of a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have gone.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this rock between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more strongly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either.
We love to hear the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best in every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
They see us as Americans in Mexico.
And in the United States we are considered Mexican.
Now, to further complicate things, so I've learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as Mexico's "ambassadors" improvised, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and pressure the political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure...
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, galloping corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be alone with this idea, folks.
Fair enough.
If some Mexicans are not yet prepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how they treated their family a lot less time ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The cease-fire between Israel and Hamas could well be a unlikely basis for peace
Could there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of the futile and usual discussions about who first began, heaps of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the Israeli metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But despite the Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their former conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab spring has left everything to taste or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been trapped in the regional uproar.
Maybe this makes your fight even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to believe that their lethal deadlock situation could be derailed.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week's clashes have strengthened the hawks on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza in one of the most miserable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could conclude that time is playing in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a renaissance regional power that had previously been the nearest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the cause of Hamas. Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf, has also done so.
Hamas' exultant members say that the half Islamic moon is surrounding Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hizbullah militia party dominates, passing through Syria, where the rebels of an ever-increasing Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, until they reach Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially in the southern side of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, unlike the most populous and fundamental of Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the lay despot who ruled in Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have too much time for Hamas.
On the other hand, Muslim Brothers are Hamas’ first brothers and their leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as the protagonist to which it cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military is concerned, they have put Hamas in place.
The Israeli Iron Cup missile system has proven to be effective and many of Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep calmer... for some time.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the last wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered, especially under the rule of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have ended the lives of some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide terrorists, partly thanks to the barrier that runs the West Bank, the main piece of aspiring territory to become a State of Palestine, and it protects Jewish settlements that continue to increase despite the fact that, according to international law, they are illegal.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party had joined an even tougher line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the pre-election period on 22 January, was in a good position.
Why pamper these Palestinian twists by giving them their own state?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, would they not shoot rockets like their compatriots in Gaza?
It is better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing is imposed, although the Arab spring could alter its calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defence budget is higher than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
Starting a war with the area's superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the fire off is a good wish and could mark the start of something.
Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, just as this week exploded a bus in Tel Aviv.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demography makes the situation worse as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution continues to be that of wise persons from both sides, the majority of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the assignment of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the cease-fire gives a little more impetus to the people who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to halt the entry of weapons into Gaza, together with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and shared Jerusalem.
Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to join.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual status category at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Again in the White House, it seems equally reluctant to devote your attention.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
