But there are more and more academics and experts in child development who praise the goodness of boredom.
According to them, it is good that, both us and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom in a good spirit?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("The Boring, An Animated History") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not so.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about the boredom dating from the first century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways," says John D. Eastwood, Professor of Psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and raising the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desiring but not being able to participate in an activity that fills you."
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do anything but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly".
Boring can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider that the problem is theirs.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what really happens to us is that we have problems concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of the magazine Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to a previous experiment in which the participants heard a tape of a person reading the article of a magazine.
Some groups listened in the room adjacent to a television program at all volumes that kept no relationship, others listened to it with the low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that heard the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario, and one of the study authors.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective pieces in a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not to get bored."
"In fact, we now know that to move or to make a tie, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help to fight it, since they make that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and hold more information than those who are forced to stand still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring movie.
But some people tend to get bored more than others.
In order to help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a "trend to boredom scale".
The scale includes issues like "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at West Florida University, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, carried out an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and his parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers said he was bored while he was in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said he was bored when he was not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boring percentages, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said that what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest altitude," largely because both children and adolescents are not given a great deal of control over what they want to do.
So, returning to my principled question: Is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, since, carried to the extreme, it can make us expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into the consumption of substances as a method to combat it, as demonstrated by research.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"The boredom is the way the brain tells you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar or cook, that'll satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your son is bored and gives him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dose," says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable beyond the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to be bored more, but boredness is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate it to something that is worth it," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
