To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth is solidified by contacting the air.
After tearing up large sulfur rocks, which in total come to weigh about 70 kilos, it carries them into two baskets of bamboo that carries on its shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters high, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb to the tortoise step, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall by the precipice.
They know that any transplant could cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who took off for the Kawah Ijen risks years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euros for every kilo of sulphur they extract
Once above, there is a passage between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, carrying tiredly the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the balance that a mining company has placed a little further down, to 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating since 1960 the volcano and, never better said, its workers, to whom 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euros) pay for each kilo of sulphur.
Then it is sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euros) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make waxes, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual it is to load 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily ports.
It takes three hours in each and ends up grinding, but allows you to join 138,000 rupees (€11.5) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is three times what I would gain in the field.
"The newspaper of the miners is very high here, where the collection of the coffee is paid to 15,000 rupees (€1.2) the day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (€ 167), "clarifies the carrier, who previously worked as a mason in the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the cut was not as hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a people close to the volcano, for a weight reason that, in Indonesia, is as strong as the sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to become Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At his 27th birthday, Anto has been playing leather in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to bill him despite covering his face with a special mask and glasses.
She has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that fire the volcano.
It's the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this smart young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other carriers, it rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop springing at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the shadows, I go down to the crater lighting up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at all weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of charge per camera that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for the beasts and not for the people," Madrusin protested, a wealthy 42-year-old carrier who has been in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Able to raise up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "everything he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and picks the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of severe illness... beyond, of course, of their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, pains on the knees and sores on the shoulders, which have been misformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only charge 50 kilos to his 53 years.
Every day, he and his companions take out 15 tons of sulfur to the volcano, which three trucks move to Tamansari's warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat road between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one who makes the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
