Concludes Unasur Summit without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) today concluded in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven assistant representatives.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources of Foreign Affairs and Presidential Affairs pointed out at an early stage that would deliver it after the closure, but later stated that it would be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When consulted by the text, they noted that the content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day only the soundless video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, restricted audio".
The little information circulated among reporters was delivered by press spokespersons from some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document published during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more data.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the pronouncement of Humala, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American Summit in the Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently required by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was also not disseminated.
On the official website of ASPA it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities endeavoured to ensure secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited the collection of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court that will direct a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to listen to the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will comply and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are taking to this international court today," Humala said, along with his Chilean partner.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake along with the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the IJC occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Covenant of Bogotá for which it had agreed to submit to the judgements of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered gravely wrong.
The summit was held with the insatisbilities of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read out the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects among South American countries for a total of $17 billion in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will "make important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for what we are expanding the residence agreements."
He reported that efforts are being made to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-priced internet access in all corners of South America, and to address the risks of natural disasters in a joint and efficient manner".
